-- Begin Enhanced Equipment Tables and its related enhanced tables
opticsIMEnhEquipmentTable OBJECT-TYPE
  SYNTAX SEQUENCE OF OpticsIMEnhEquipmentEntry
  MAX-ACCESS         not-accessible
  STATUS             current
  DESCRIPTION
    "This table is and enhancement of opticsIMEquipmentTable and it contains
     the information related to the resources that represent the physical
     components of a managed element, including replaceable components."
::= { opticsIMEqptMibObject 14 }

opticsIMEnhEquipmentEntry OBJECT-TYPE
  SYNTAX              OpticsIMEnhEquipmentEntry
  MAX-ACCESS          not-accessible
  STATUS              current
  DESCRIPTION
    "An entry of the enhanced equipment table. Each entry (row) corresponds to
     a physical component of a managed element (racks, subracks, slots/boards,
     sub-slots/daughter boards/drawers, optical/electrical modules).
     During the commissioning phase the whole set of instances is created by
     the network element itself.
     Each entry may be instantiated or exist without the presence of the
     physical resources. In this case the operationalState will be disabled.
     When the resource is physically removed, the corresponding equipment
     object is not automatically deleted. When a resource is physically
     installed and no corresponding equipment object has been created, no self
     instantiation is performed.
     The opticsEquipmentActual attribute represents the type of equipment which
     is physically present. This attribute assume the 'EMPTY' value when either
     the resource is not physically present or the NE is unable to identify the
     equipment type.
     The opticsEquipmentExpected attribute contains the type of equipment that
     the managing system expects to be present.It is set by the agent as a side
     effect of setting the opticsEquipmentExpectedTypeId associated to.
     The opticsEquipmentExpectedTypeId attribute value of each instance may be
     set according to a planned or default configuration known by the NE and
     represents the identifier of the type of equipment expected to be present.
     If no configuration is wanted then the opticsEquipmentExpectedTypeId shall
     be set to 0 corresponding to the 'EMPTY' value.
     If the opticsEquipmentExpected attribute value is set to a non 'EMPTY'
     value, and if the equipment is not physically present an alarm
     notification is sent with the probableCause of 'replaceableUnitMissing'.
     When there is a mismatch in the contents of the opticsEquipmentActual and
     the equipmentExpected attribute, an alarm notification with probableCause
     'replaceableUnitTypeMismatch' will be raised.
     The opticsEquipmentExpected value of 'EMPTY' (no type) does not match any
     other value for opticsEquipmentActual except 'EMPTY'.
     In case opticsEquipmentExpected is 'EMPTY' and opticsEquipmentActual is
     different from 'EMPTY' an alarm notification with probableCause
     'unconfiguredEquipmentPresent' will be raised (exception to mismatch case).
     If the opticsEquipmentExpected attribute value is set to 'EMPTY' and the
     NE is not able to identify the resource which is physically present
     (opticsEquipmentActual = 'EMPTY'), an alarm notification is raised with
     probableCause 'replaceableUnitProblem'.
     Based on the value of the opticsEquipmentExpected attribute, the
     functional objects implemented by the physical instance are automatically
     created inside the NE and are included in the list of the affected object
     pointed by the related instance.
     In case opticsEquipmentExpected is set to 'EMPTY', no object will be
     included in the affectedObject list.
     When, for reconfiguration purposes, the opticsEquipmentExpected attribute
     is changed by the managing system the whole set of functional objects (TPs)
     present in the related list of affectedObjects and associated to the
     previous value of the opticsEquipmentExpected are deleted and the new set,
     associated to the new value of equipmentExpected, are created.
     Change of the opticsEquipmentExpected of an instance is only permitted
     when that instance is in locked administrativeState and if corresponding
     functional objects can be deleted (e.g. the deletion  should fail if one
     of these is used as a timing reference).
     When a resource is physically removed and replaced by another resource of
     a different type for reconfiguration purposes the new resource can be
     brought into service only after the managing system has changed the
     opticsEquipmentExpected value of the corresponding instance matching the
     new opticsEquipmentActual value.
     The opticsEquipmentAdministrativeState attribute may have the following
     values: locked, and unlocked.
     This attribute reflects  the management authorization for the resource to
     perform its function.
     When an instance enters  the locked administrativeState then all affected
     functional objects enter the disabled operationalState.
     The opticsEquipmentOperationalState attribute may assume two values:
     enabled and disabled, according to the intrinsic capability of the
     resource to perform its function.
     On detection of equipment failures  (e.g. replaceableUnitMissing,
     replaceableTypeMismatch, replaceableUnitProblem), the whole set of TPs
     included on the affectedObject list, should change their operationalState
     attribute to 'disabled'. In case of equipment involved in a Equipment
     Protection Switching, the TPs included on the affectedObject list should
     change their operationalState attribute to 'disabled' only for the active
     equipment (not for the stand-by one).
     When an entry of this table enters in disabled operationalState then all
     affected objects enter the disabled operationalState.
     The  opticsEquipmentBoardReset  attribute allows the remote board reset.
     The opticsEquipmentRxLinkStatus and opticsEquipmentTxLinkStatus attributes
     are related to the management of link failure alarm (for instance modelled
     by  the opticsIMAlarmReceiverFailure alarm).
     When a link failure alarm raises,  the link alarm localization is done by
     these attributes, analysing the links and the string characters. This
     association rule must be described  within product specification."
  INDEX    { opticsEquipmentPosition }
::= { opticsIMEnhEquipmentTable 1 }

